l="alternate" type="application/atom+xml" title="Interview: Girls' Mama's Boy" /><link href="http://www.dose.ca/5465805.ATOM" rel="self" type="application/atom+xml" title="Interview: Girls' Mama's Boy" /><entry Status="FREE"><id>tag:www.dose.ca:content=5465805</id><title type="html">Interview: Girls' Mama's Boy</title><summary type="html"></summary><published>2011-09-27T00:00:00Z</published><updated>2011-09-27T20:01:42Z</updated><author><name>Eric Koreen</name></author><link href="Interview+Girls+Mama/5465805/story.html" Abstract="Girls frontman Christopher Owens on how his relationship with his mom influenced sophomore album Father, Son, Holy Ghost." Credit="Eric Koreen" rel="alternate" type="text/html" title="[ more ]" /><link href="5465807.bin" Abstract="Girls play Toronto Sept. 27 and Vancouver Oct. 4." Credit="Handout" rel="enclosure" type="image/jpeg" title="Girls" /><link href="http://www.dose.ca/music/index.html" Abstract="Get the latest music news, interviews and album reviews" Credit="" rel="related" type="text/html" title="Get the latest music news, interviews and album reviews" /><link href="http://www.twitter.com/DoseDotCa" Abstract="Follow Dose.ca on Twitter" Credit="" rel="related" type="text/html" title="Follow Dose.ca on Twitter" /><category term="Music" label="ConTopic" /><category term="Postmedia News" label="Distributor" /><category term="STRY" label="ContentTypeCode" /><category term="DOSE" label="Catalog" /><category term="Y" label="Comments" /><category term="UTF8" label="Format" /><category relevance="13" term="San Antonio" label="City" /><category relevance="15" term="Toronto" label="City" /><category relevance="19" term="Vancouver" label="City" /><category relevance="13" term="Washington, DC" label="City" /><category relevance="11" term="Asia" label="Continent" /><category relevance="11" term="Europe" label="Continent" /><category relevance="11" term="United States" label="Country" /><category relevance="23" term="Freud , Lucian" label="Individual" /><category relevance="12" term="Newman , Randy" label="Individual" /><category relevance="100" term="Owens , Christopher" label="Individual" /><category relevance="100" term="0~Christopher Owens~Lucian Freud~Vancouver~Toronto" label="InformQString" /><category relevance="14" term="Canadian Tour" label="Misc" /><category relevance="11" term="OFWGKTA" label="Organization" /><category relevance="11" term="The Beach Boys" label="Organization" /><category relevance="100" term="Christopher Owens" label="Person" /><category relevance="23" term="Lucian Freud" label="Person" /><category relevance="12" term="Randy Newman" label="Person" /><category relevance="11" term="Texas" label="State" /><content type="xhtml"><div id="1">&lt;P&gt;There is a moment on &amp;quot;Honey Bunny,&amp;quot; the opening track on Girls' sophomore album, &lt;I&gt;Father, Son, Holy Ghost&lt;/I&gt;, when frontman Christopher Owens disassembles his trademark shtick. As he often does, Owens is singing about finding love. Jarringly, at the bridge, he stops. He begins singing about his mother. &amp;quot;That woman loved me,&amp;quot; Owens sings. &amp;quot;I need a woman who loves me, me, me, me, me, me.&amp;quot;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;object height="81" width="100%"&gt; &lt;param name="movie" value="http://player.soundcloud.com/player.swf?url=http%3A%2F%2Fapi.soundcloud.com%2Ftracks%2F21727991"&gt;&lt;/param&gt; &lt;param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"&gt;&lt;/param&gt; &lt;embed allowscriptaccess="always" height="81" src="http://player.soundcloud.com/player.swf?url=http%3A%2F%2Fapi.soundcloud.com%2Ftracks%2F21727991" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" width="100%"&gt;&lt;/embed&gt; &lt;/object&gt;  &lt;span&gt;&lt;a href="http://soundcloud.com/artsandcraftsmx/girls-honey-bunny"&gt;Girls - Honey Bunny&lt;/a&gt; by &lt;a href="http://soundcloud.com/artsandcraftsmx"&gt;artsandcraftsmx&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;P&gt;It is the kind of moment that could earn Owens a concert hall's worth of awkward eyes. A segue from finding love to a mother's love. On the surface, it is all very Oedipal.&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P&gt;&amp;quot;I can think of one person who would be on my side. His name is Lucian Freud,&amp;quot; Owens said last week from Washington, D.C. &amp;quot;Or is that the painter? No, the other Freud [Sigmund], with the mother theories. I wasn't trying to make a reference to that. It just came out very naturally.&amp;quot;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P&gt;Indeed, there are a few songs in which Owens slightly alters his (admitted) woe-is-me, search-for-love formula, and looks at his relationship with his mother. It is not the only change for Girls -- the band's debut was full of intricate, little pop songs, though &lt;I&gt;Father&lt;/I&gt; allows the songs and instrumentation to breathe a bit more -- but it is the most visceral because of Owens' personal history.&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P&gt;The Coles Notes version: Owens was born into the Children of God cult, constantly moving around Asia and Europe in his childhood. Before he was born, his mother refused to take his brother to the hospital for the pneumonia that eventually killed him. Owens' mother was also a prostitute for a time, although Owens clarified that it was not that simple. She eventually left the cult, and now lives in San Antonio as a refugee worker.&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P&gt;Owens did not listen to pop music until he was 16, when he broke free from the cult and moved to Texas. A local millionaire took Owens in and encouraged him to immerse himself in the arts. Ten years later, Owens has crafted an album that has earned a 9.3 out of 10, a score not given out more than three or four times per year, from the taste-making website &lt;I&gt;Pitchfork.&lt;/I&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P&gt;It is heavy stuff, surely enough to make Owens bitter about his upbringing and his mother. And yet: &amp;quot;I didn't really try to start writing about my mom. In my mind, I was subconsciously reflecting about -- and this is something people were asking about a lot of the time when I was doing interviews for the first record -- why is there so much need to find love [in his lyrics.] 'What's wrong with you?' basically,&amp;quot; Owens said. &amp;quot;In the song, this wasn't planned out, but I was writing it and thinking, 'Where is this coming from?' And it led to this bridge that explained why somebody would maybe be looking for that kind of unconditional love, real love, where you've felt it before and why you would need it again. That's why that came up.&amp;quot;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P&gt;The album's fifth track, &amp;quot;My Ma,&amp;quot; is even more of a tribute to his mother. (Although its opening lyrics would not have you believe it: &amp;quot;Oh god, I'm tired/And my heart is broken.&amp;quot;) The song, complete with a slow-burn jam at the end, has Owens looking for meaning in his life, and tying it back to his mother. It is a bit of an apology to his mother, after one interview with a British outlet painted Owens, in his own words, as &amp;quot;a ragamuffin son of a prostitute rolling around in the mud.&amp;quot;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;object height="81" width="100%"&gt; &lt;param name="movie" value="http://player.soundcloud.com/player.swf?url=http%3A%2F%2Fapi.soundcloud.com%2Ftracks%2F22845188"&gt;&lt;/param&gt; &lt;param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"&gt;&lt;/param&gt; &lt;embed allowscriptaccess="always" height="81" src="http://player.soundcloud.com/player.swf?url=http%3A%2F%2Fapi.soundcloud.com%2Ftracks%2F22845188" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" width="100%"&gt;&lt;/embed&gt; &lt;/object&gt;  &lt;span&gt;&lt;a href="http://soundcloud.com/artsandcraftsmx/girls-my-ma"&gt;Girls - My Ma&lt;/a&gt; by &lt;a href="http://soundcloud.com/artsandcraftsmx"&gt;artsandcraftsmx&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;P&gt;&amp;quot;She was very hurt by these things. The worst part was, she didn't say, 'How could you talk about these things?' She just assumed, 'Oh, you hate me now,'&amp;quot; Owens said. &amp;quot;'My Ma' is about a block of time where I made a huge effort to make sure she knew that I'm not upset. There was a bit of sensationalism that happened on that story. I've never yelled at her. She's never yelled at me. We've had a really good relationship. The song is kind of reaching out to this topic. It's about the healing process that's happening.&amp;quot;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P&gt;As with his lyrics, Owens is as confessional as anybody in music in his interviews. And considering his history, there is the risk that Girls will be defined by the story, not the art. But it is the music, which bathes in its influences ranging from Randy Newman to the Beach Boys to whisky-drenched country to psychedelia to soul, that deserves attention.&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P&gt;&amp;quot;I think it's done a good thing. It's drawn a lot of attention,&amp;quot; Owens said. &amp;quot;And then it's down to the music. That's what I do. I hear about, say, a kid like Tyler [the Creator of Odd Future]. There's backstory there. And that's how you get drawn in. What you do is then you listen to the album. And you like it or you don't.&amp;quot;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P&gt;&lt;B&gt;&lt;I&gt;Girls' Canadian Tour Dates Include&lt;/I&gt;&lt;/B&gt;&lt;I&gt;: &lt;/I&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P&gt;&lt;I&gt;Toronto, Sept. 27 &lt;/I&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P&gt;&lt;I&gt;Vancouver, Oct. 4&lt;/I&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;iframe width="425" height="239" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/ze6rg4ixjOI" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen&gt;&lt;/iframe&gt;</div></content><rights type="text">Copyright (c) National Post</rights><source><title type="html">Interview: Girls' Mama's Boy</title><subtitle type="html">Girls frontman Christopher Owens on how his relationship with his mom influenced sophomore album Father, Son, Holy Ghost.</subtitle><id>tag:www.dose.ca:content=5465805</id><rights type="html">Copyright (c) National Post</rights><updated>2011-09-27T20:01:42Z</updated><category term="Music" label="ConTopic" /><category term="Postmedia News" label="Distributor" /